task_description:
In the  experiment, each participant is given 36 different proposals to respond to. Each is designated by a trial number in the data set This gives 36 instances for the learnable parameters to be trained. There is also a pretask where the participant finds a number of tokens that correspond to their contribution to the group. This is designated by the variable "token_self". The other variable, "token_opp", is the number of tokens found the opponent's and represents the opoonents contribution to the shared pot that will be later divided by the opponent.

Note that in each trial there is a variable amount of money in the combined earning, so that two equal split_self variables do not represent the same "fairness".

Below is the description of each variable in the dataset, which will be followed by information about the data type of the variable:

trial_type = how much was the contribution [1 = equal, 2 = opponent more, 3 = participant more]
trial_role = the role of the participant [1 = responder, 2 = proposer]
token_opp = number of tokens found by the opponent
token_self = number of tokens found by the participant
combined_earning = amount of money earned in total (note that each token found is £3)
split_opp = the proposed share of the opponent (in £)
split_self = the proposed share for the participant (in £)
splitperc_opp = same but in %
split_perc_self = same but in %
accept = whether the participant responded accept (1) or reject (0)
accepted_amount = if accepted, what is the amount gain (in £)
accepted_perc = same as above but in %
proposed_perc = when participant is the proposer, what is the % proposed to the opponent

Step-by-step reasoning:
1. Key psychological mechanisms:
  Participants adjust their proposals based on their perceived contribution compared to their opponent. When the opponent’s contribution is higher (i.e., token_opp > token_self), participants tend to be more generous by proposing a higher percentage (i.e., higher proposed_perc) for the opponent. Conversely, when their own contribution is higher, they tend to be less generous.
2. Mechanism interactions:
  A fairness norm is assumed whereby an equal split corresponds to a 50% offer to the opponent. Deviations from this norm depend on the difference in token counts (token_opp – token_self), scaled by the sum (token_opp + token_self) to factor in relative contributions. A sensitivity parameter modulates the degree to which this perceived fairness imbalance affects the proposal.
3. Mathematical form:
  The proposal is modeled as a baseline of 50 plus an adjustment term that captures the normalized difference in token contributions, scaled by a learnable parameter (β). This ensures that when contributions are equal the proposal is 50%, and deviations are proportional to the fairness imbalance.
4. Parameter calibration:
  Only one learnable parameter β (beta) is introduced. It governs sensitivity to differences in token contributions. Finite bounds are specified for β.
5. Mapping to behavior:
  The observable "proposed_perc" is predicted from token_opp and token_self via the formula:
  predicted_proposed_perc = 50 + β × 50 × ((token_opp – token_self) / (token_opp + token_self))
  This formula utilizes all variables within the equation and meets the constraint of a single learnable parameter.

The final model specification is as follows:

<MODEL>
predicted_proposed_perc = 50 + beta * 50 * ((token_opp - token_self)/(token_opp + token_self))
</MODEL>

import json

def simulate_model(trial_data, beta=0):
    model_predictions = []
    for trial in trial_data:
        token_opp = trial.get("token_opp", 0)
        token_self = trial.get("token_self", 0)

            predicted_proposed_perc = 50  # Avoid division by zero
